{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657733"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20644"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20644"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94173"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77273"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11712"},{"type":"tags","id":"12532"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32289"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94173"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils are critical components of the innate immune system that respond rapidly to infection. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation and function of neutrophil extracellular traps?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Release of cytoplasmic granules without chromatin involvement","Production of reactive oxygen species within phagolysosomes","Formation of fibrillar networks that trap and kill microbes","Secretion of intact nuclear DNA without cell death","Aggregation of neutrophils to form physical barriers"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of fibrillar networks that trap and kill microbes\u003C/strong\u003E. Neutrophil extracellular traps (NETs) are extracellular fibrillar networks composed of decondensed chromatin decorated with antimicrobial proteins and enzymes. They function to concentrate antimicrobial substances at infection sites, trap microorganisms, and prevent their spread.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease of cytoplasmic granules without chromatin involvement\u003C/strong\u003E - While neutrophil degranulation is a separate antimicrobial mechanism, NETs specifically involve nuclear chromatin as a key structural component.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of reactive oxygen species within phagolysosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - Although reactive oxygen species (ROS) are essential for triggering NET formation, they act as signalling molecules in this process rather than being confined to phagolysosomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of intact nuclear DNA without cell death\u003C/strong\u003E - NET formation involves chromatin decondensation and nuclear envelope rupture, leading to neutrophil death. The DNA is not secreted intact but undergoes significant structural changes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAggregation of neutrophils to form physical barriers\u003C/strong\u003E - NETs are produced by individual neutrophils and do not involve cellular aggregation to form barriers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe process of NET formation (NETosis) begins with ROS-dependent activation of an arginine deaminase that converts arginines to citrulline, leading to chromatin decondensation. Enzymes like myeloperoxidase and elastase enter the nucleus, causing further chromatin decondensation, culminating in nuclear envelope rupture and chromatin release. This process results in neutrophil death. The released NETs contain histones, DNA, and antimicrobial proteins that help combat infections but may also contribute to autoimmune diseases like systemic lupus erythematosus by providing a source of nuclear antigens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neutrophil extracellular traps (NETs) are fibrillar networks that concentrate antimicrobial substances and trap microbes at infection sites.","NET formation involves reactive oxygen species-dependent chromatin decondensation, nuclear envelope rupture, and eventual neutrophil cell death.","NETs contain nuclear chromatin, histones, DNA, and antimicrobial proteins that help combat infections but may also contribute to autoimmune diseases."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 83-84"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77273"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20644"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77273"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T13:10:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T13:11:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13520"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94173"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://ap